Course1 : Foundation of information¶

Assignment: Data extraction and analysis from social media platform Youtube ( 30 Marks )

Problem statement

Videos are a fast growing medium where people communicate, share knowledge, showcase skills etc. YouTube is one of the biggest platforms which hosts videos. The YouTube platform hosts content from many different professions/arts/ cultures across the world.

People can express their opinion about the video in the form of likes, dislikes, comments which are features provided by the YouTube platform which provides the information on the sentiment about the video.

The assignment involves the steps on programmatic data extraction from YouTube on which analysis can be conducted to understand various attributes related to a video.

Steps to be performed

1.b Install the Google API python client (2 marks)

refer to the supporting link on how to create YouTube API Key

Reference link : https://developers.google.com/youtube/v3/quickstart/python

# 2.a
from googleapiclient.discovery import build

API_KEY = 'AIzaSyAcuHim7iwgi55UCEEHYspBCOpAnA45RqY'
youtube = build('youtube', 'v3', developerKey=API_KEY)


query_string = 'avatar movie'

# Making a request to the search API endpoint
search_request = youtube.search().list(
    q=query_string,
    part='id,snippet',
    maxResults=1  
)

search_response = search_request.execute()   #response
#print(search_response['items'])

for item in search_response['items']:
    id = item['id']
    snippet = item['snippet']
    channel_id = snippet['channelId']
    video_description = snippet['description']
    channel_title = snippet['channelTitle']
    video_title = snippet['title']
    print(f"ID: {id} \n\n")
    print(f"SNIPPET: {snippet} \n\n")
    print(f"CHANNEL ID: {channel_id} \n\n")
    print(f"VIDEO DESCRIPTION: {video_description} \n\n")
    print(f"CHANNEL TITLE: {channel_title} \n\n")
    print(f"VIDEO TITLE: {video_title} \n\n")

Output expected: video ID, title, no of views, no of likes,no of comments exported to CSV file

Reference link: https://developers.google.com/youtube/v3/docs/videos/list

# < code block > 
#2.b


import csv
data_row_list = []

heading_fields = ['Video ID','Title','No of Views','No of Likes', 'No of Comments']

def get_statistics(video_id):
    video_stats_request = youtube.videos().list(
        part='snippet,statistics',
        id = video_id,
    )
    video_stats_response = video_stats_request.execute()
    row_as_dict = {}
    item = video_stats_response['items'][0]
    video_id = item['id']
    title = item['snippet']['title']
    total_views = int(item['statistics']['viewCount'])
    total_likes = int(item['statistics']['likeCount'])
    total_comments = int(item['statistics']['commentCount'])
    row_as_dict['Video ID'] = video_id
    row_as_dict['Title'] = title
    row_as_dict['No of Views'] = total_views
    row_as_dict['No of Likes'] = total_likes
    row_as_dict['No of Comments'] = total_comments
    data_row_list.append(row_as_dict)
    print(row_as_dict)

#making request
search_request = youtube.search().list(
    q='avatar movie',
    part='id,snippet',
    regionCode = 'US',
    order='relevance',
    type='video',
    maxResults=50
)
search_response = search_request.execute()
for item in search_response['items']:
    video_id = item['id']['videoId']
    get_statistics(video_id)

#print(data_row_list)


with open('stats_top_50.csv','w') as csv_file:
    writer_instance = csv.DictWriter(csv_file,fieldnames=heading_fields)
    writer_instance.writeheader()
    writer_instance.writerows(data_row_list)
    print("EXPORTED TO CSV FILE stats_top_50.csv")

# < code block >
#3.b Print response using pprint :

import pprint
formatted_responses_list = []
for video in top_10_comments_data:

    video_id = video['Video ID']
    print("\n\n")
    comments_request = youtube.commentThreads().list(
            part="snippet",
            videoId=video_id,
        )
    comments_response = comments_request.execute()
    formatted_response = pprint.pformat(comments_response)
    formatted_responses_list.append(formatted_response)
    pprint.pprint(comments_response)

3.c Write a program to export the output of question 3.b in JSON file format and submit the file as part of the assignment (3 marks)

In [77]:
# < code block >
#3.c Export to JSON:

import json
#creating empty JSON file
with open("output_from_pprint.json",'w') as output_file:
    print("Creating output_from_pprint.json file to export the responses")
    pass

for i in range(len(formatted_responses_list)):
    
    #appending the formatted_responses from 3.b
    with open("output_from_pprint.json",'a') as output_file:
        json.dump(formatted_responses_list[i],output_file)
    print(f"Copying formatted response related to Video: {i+1} to output_from_pprint.json file")
print("Successfully finished exporting responses to the output_from_pprint.json file ")

3.d Write a function to get the likes vs views ratio of the top 10 videos obtained in 3.a with the highest comments (3 marks)

In [78]:
# < code block >
#3.d Likes vs Views Ratio Function:

def get_likes_vs_views_ratio(top_10_comments_list):

    for i in range(len(top_10_comments_list)):

        video_id = top_10_comments_list[i]['Video ID']
        video_likes = top_10_comments_list[i]['No of Likes']
        video_views = top_10_comments_list[i]['No of Views']
        print(f"{i+1}. Likes vs Views ratio of video with Video ID: {video_id} = {video_likes/video_views}")
